WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Features You Can't Live Without

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hi, everyone. I'm here to talk about dplyr 1.1.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.000
But really, I'm actually here to talk about reducing friction

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.000
in the latest version of the dplyr release.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:19.000
And by friction, I really just mean anything

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.000
that kind of takes you out of that flow state

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.000
of just writing code.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.000
We've actually reduced friction in three different ways

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.000
in this release, one in case when,

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:30.000
one in some big changes to grouping,

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
and then some really cool things with joins.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.000
So we're going to jump right in with kind of an easy win

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
that we had with case when.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.000
So my wife actually is a big tidyverse user.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.000
This is really cool for me because it means

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.000
I get a lot of one-on-one feedback

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.000
about exactly what's going wrong.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
And she writes a lot of case when statements

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
that look like this, and what's going wrong is this.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.000
If you haven't seen this before,

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.000
case when is fairly strict about the types

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:00.000
of the things on the right-hand side.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
So she would mix a character like large and small

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
with na as a logical na here, and it would complain.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.000
It would say, no, you have to use this very special

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.000
na character thing instead.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.000
If you use case when a lot, you've probably seen this.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.000
And this isn't something we typically expect people to know.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
It makes case when harder to use and harder to teach.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.000
So as of 1.1, a very easy win is that case when

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:25.000
is now much less strict about the things

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:27.000
on the right-hand side.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
So this just works.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:36.000
All right, let's move on and talk about grouping.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.000
So I think this section is really cool.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:41.000
I play a lot of Mario Kart, so I came up with a question

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
of which character, Mario or Luigi and so on,

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.000
had the most wins on a single track?

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:50.000
So if you have this imaginary races data set,

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
I'm looking for just one row back here.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.000
I want the character on a track with the most number of wins.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:01:59.000
The way you might get here is say,

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.000
well, I'm going to group by character and track.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
I'm going to compute the total number of wins,

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
and then I'm going to slice out the top win row.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:11.000
If you were to actually run this code, though,

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.000
there's a bug in here.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
I only wanted Luigi at Moo Moo Farm, yes,

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
that is a real track, with 305 wins.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
That's the only one I wanted back, but I got multiple rows.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
I actually end up with one per character here.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And the reason this happens is that Summarize, by default,

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
just peels off one layer of grouping.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:36.000
So when we go into that SliceMax call,

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.000
we're actually still grouped by character.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So we end up with one row per character.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.000
Now if you're a keen dplyr user, you know what the problem is.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.000
I forgot to ungroup.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.000
I'm probably not the only one who's forgotten to ungroup.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
All of you have forgotten to ungroup.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:01.000
Remembering for the 648th time that if dplyr does something weird,

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.000
it is always because you have forgotten to ungroup.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.000
It has become such a thing that people just made it a habit

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.000
of group by, do the thing, ungroup,

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
and every time they call something in dplyr.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
It has even become such a thing that it has joined

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Alison Horst to artwork, where she is begging you

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:24.000
not to forget to invite ungroup to the party.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
All right, so we took a step back and we said,

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.000
is there anything we could do about this to make it

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
so you never have to remember to ungroup ever again?

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.000
We've actually taken a page out of the Data Table Playbook,

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
and as of 1.1, you can now write the grouping

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.000
in line with the Summarize call.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:50.000
This is pretty cool because Races goes in to Summarize

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
as an ungrouped DataFrame, and it comes out of Summarize

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
as an ungrouped DataFrame, full stop,

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
no strange edge cases whatsoever.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
This means that Summarize now no longer has to message you

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
about what it's doing with the grouping,

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
and you never have to worry about that .groups argument

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:09.000
if you don't want to.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Now, group by is not going away, there's no need to worry,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.000
but we think this new syntax is pretty cool.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
All of the major dplyr verbs support it.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:22.000
Lastly, I just want to talk very quickly about joins.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.000
I don't have much time here, but there is a lot here.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
We've introduced rolling joins, inequality joins,

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
overlap joins, these new arguments that help you

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.000
with quality control, like one-to-one or one-to-many.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.000
And the most I can do is just show you some questions

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.000
and say, look, these are things that were really hard

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.000
to answer with dplyr before, but we've reduced that friction

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
to essentially make them one-liners now.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:48.000
If you ever work with time series or you ever work

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
with genomic data, these are things that you can do now,

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:54.000
and I think you should really look at Hadley's

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.000
R for Data Science book.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
He's written a great new section on joins,

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.000
where we've introduced this new join by helper

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:06.000
that can let you express very complex joins very easily.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
So to recap, we've talked about these three things.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
There is a lot more in the 1.1 release that I didn't

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:14.000
even get to touch, but we have written a whole series

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
of 1.1 blog posts, so I encourage you to go

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
to tidyverse.org and check those out.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Thank you so much.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Thank you.

